Some naming systems put the most significant name on the right, some
put the most significant on the left.  This is generally recognized as
one of the facts of life, although there are some arguments about
which is better.

Some mail systems attempt to recognize which end of a name has the
most significant component by recognizing "most significant"
components.  This is generally recognized as a bad idea, but it
persists.

Thus, if you use names which begin with components which also happen
to be "well-known" top level names, you can expect difficulties due to
their broken code.  Lest you feel too generous towards them, they once
told me I should rename E.ISI.EDU since E was a "recognized" alias
for Spain.

paul

